   Leaving the professional politics aside.  I just want to comment on what &quot;free speech&quot; really means.  <br>
   Most people believe that it means   &quot; HEY!!  I can say &quot;A-N-Y-T-H-I-N-G&quot; that I want to and nobody can do anything about it!! &quot;<br>
    This is a tenet of our Bill of Rights, one of the rights almost every one of us prizes about all else.<br>
    In real life however,we must add the line  &quot; and based on what you say, the others with &quot;free speech&quot; can and WILL judge you and act accordingly.&quot; <br>
<br>
  Based on this, lets look at current French relations.<br>
I think most folks could agree that, stereotypically at least, Americans think that the French are a rude and obnoxious, smelly people...  And the French think of Americans as arrogant and self centered.<br>
   Once Jaques Chirac openly opposed the U.S.A. before the United Nations and promised a Veto of ANY resolution which the U.S.A. would or could put forth, the American public (at least the more outspoken parts) decided that since Jaques wouldn't give the US a chance, we would respond in kind.<br>
  With this stereotype already in place, it is easy to see why much of the American populous (again, at least the more outspoken parts)  are banning/boycotting  French economic products and in general are flaming the French.<br>
  Jaques spoke his part and despite his freedom of choices and opinions, he was judged harshly.<br>
<br>
     Popular country musicians, the &quot;Dixie Chicks&quot; lead singer, Natalie Maines, utilized her right to free speech and told her audience that she was &quot;Ashamed that George Bush was from Texas&quot;.   While she had the RIGHT to say that without US Government persecution, The Dixie Chicks CD's are not currently getting any airtime on MANY of the nations radio stations and in one case, a Houston, Texas radio station is collection thier CD's in a Dumpster and will be mailing the CD's back to the group when they return home from thier European tour.<br>
<br>
Sorry for the rant, but I've heard an awful lot of people  (mostly demonstrators, and from both sides) whining about how they have &quot; Free Speech&quot; ..  In reality they do have rights to Speak freely, but I wish that they would also remember that so does everyone else..  And if you're an idiot and open your mouth to say the wrong thing at the wrong time, rest assured, people for better or worse will judge you and you will pay the social consequences even if you're within your rights.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
All that being said...<br>
 Iraq     <br>
       IMHO, I believe that the current war in Iraq was and is the only way to remove Hussein from power.  It needed doing, he was/ is a mass murderer. <br>
   Some tout the &quot;Cost of War&quot; and protest about all the &quot;lives that will be lost, both in our troops and Iraqi civilians&quot;.  I agree, the cost will be grave.  But what about the &quot;Cost of Peace&quot;?  Would we stand by for over 12 years and let Hussein kill his own people, and let thousands of Iraqi's die so that we Americans can stay at home?<br>
  Yeah, if we hadn't got involved, our soldiers wouldn't be in harms way..  We could wait Sadaam out, eventually, he would be selling chemicals or biologicals to the highest bidder, and our civilians would pay the price.   Either way, folks die, war isn't pretty.<br>
 I do not, however, agree with the political steps taken to begin this War.  Now that it is upon us, I do support it, reguardless of how we arrived here.<br>
      I do not believe that Al-Quaeda and Sadaam are linked.  At least not beyond financial ties and possibly the purchase of weaponry.   Al-Quaeda is not Sunni Muslim, yet they are primarliy Muslim.  Saddam came from a primarily Sunni upbringing but has declared himself to be Athiest and the mass killing of the Kurdish sect of muslims in the Northern reaches of his country was done with Sarin and VX gases. ( Both are chemical weapons of mass destruction.)<br>
<br>
As for Other topics, <br>
<br>
       Protesters for or against this war...  If you feel strongly either way, show it..  If that means sit in's or peaceful protests, then go for it.  Do not however, endanger other Americans by your short sighted actions.<br>
    What does blocking a street gain you?  Some lil old lady who supports your cause, may have a heart attack..  If you block the street and ambulances cant get to her..  You are responsible for manslaughter.<br>
      Break the law, you go to jail..  Throw a bottle at a cop?  Set something on fire?  Destroy property? ..  I hope you get to spend alot of time behind bars...  that is uncalled for.<br>
<br>
     The French..  IMHO, the French people, more or less, aren't any better or worse than we are.  The French government, most noteably, Jaques Chirac, has made some very poor political choices.  If you don't like them, let him know it.  But why slam the French public?  What does it gain you when it's thier leaders who are the idiots? <br>
<br>
  The Dixie Chicks..  Hmm .. Natalie Maines and company make good music, but thier lead singer lacks tact...  I wonder, in dollars and future sales, just how many THOUSANDS of dollars that one comment has cost thier group..  I hope they think it was worth every penny.<br>
<br>
    I like my Steak medium rare, my Miller lite cold and in a bottle, Everquest anytime of day or night, and prefer briefs to boxers...  <br>
<br>
 Thats about my opinion on everything, I'll shut up now..  If you liked it, great, if not, I hope you got a good laugh.. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
